Parking is a challenge. The variety of appetizers, entrees, sandwiches, salads and drink options are good. Portions were small/average. Food arrived somewhat warm but not hot. Mixed drink menu selections were creative but were average to small in size and therefore overpriced. Wait staff were busy but friendly and very accommodating. Our male server seemed flustered and overwhelmed and less than friendly. The interior and exterior of the building are esthetically pleasing. Lighting was lovely and there is beautiful wood throughout. The dining area and bar were exceptionally clean and our table linens and place settings were spotless. Our bill for our party of 6 was over $200.  Two ordered a seasonal mixed drink, one a draft beer with three drinking only water. Five from our party ordered Steak Frites with truffle fries. Three of the five received lettuce wedges with blue cheese (1/2 a head of lettuce quartered and plated with a smearing of blue cheese) while two opted for quinoa. All stated both were disappointing. Our sixth at the table ordered the grilled chicken sandwich on wheat. Chicken breast was 1/4 inch and was dry and overcooked. Wheat toast was burnt. Truffle fries served to all were beautifully flavored but were no longer warm when served. All five ordering the Steak Frites stated their steak, while portions were very small, the flavor was excellent and all five felt their's was cooked perfectly. I really wanted to love the food as much as I did the aesthetics and design but unfortunately this time, I did not. I did enjoy their wait staff, ambiance, cleanliness, and pleasing designs enough to give their menu another try. I will update after my next visit.

The service was 5 star, the food a generous 3. The oysters were laughable, we've never seen them so small!  Again, the server saved the day by recognizing they were subpar and bringing 3 extra to the table. I had high hopes for the steak until it arrived medium instead of medium rare. I don't mind paying for good food if there is value to the price tag. Unfortunately, the tiny oysters and overdone steak made it a less than stellar experience. The server, bless her heart, comped a glass of wine to say how sorry she was, but really if Big Grove wants to be a higher end restaurant choice downtown they need to step up their food preparation. The manager did come out after we paid the check to say he was sorry things weren't up to par but that the regular grill person had a death in the family. I'm truly sorry for that person's loss, however a restaurant has to be able to provide adequate food regardless of unexpected circumstances.
